OL,6,G1936 The world's first regular
OL,7,Gtelevision service is officially
OL,8,Glaunched by the BBC. Based at
OL,9,GAlexandra Palace in London, the
OL,10,Gservice initially alternated (on a
OL,11,Gweekly basis) between two systems:
OL,12,GBaird's 240-line mechanical system;
OL,13,Gthe Marconi-EMI 405-line all-
OL,14,Gelectronic system. Studio A was the
OL,15,Ghome of the Marconi-EMI equipment;
OL,16,GStudio B was used for Baird
OL,17,Gtransmissions.JAs well as the obvious
OL,18,Gshortcomings of the Baird system in
OL,19,Gterms of picture resolution, it also
OL,20,Ginvolved an intermediate film process
OL,21,Gwhereby images had to be processed on
OL,22,Gto celluloid before being played-out.
OL,23,GThis rather cumbersome element was a
OL,24,Gsource of much frustration for
OL,25,Gproducers and directors.JThe BBC soon
OL,26,Gintroduced 'London television
